<div id="raksha" class="festival-card">
    <h2>Raksha Bandhan</h2>
    <p>Long ago, when Lord Krishna hurt his finger, Draupadi tore a piece of her saree and tied it around his wound. Krishna was touched by her gesture and promised to protect her forever. Since then, Raksha Bandhan has been celebrated as a festival of love, trust, and protection between brothers and sisters.</p>
    <img src="https://img.freepik.com/premium-photo/happy-raksha-bandhan-cartoon-with-sister-tying-festival-celebration-card-background-greeting-card_1157715-6677.jpg?w=2000" alt="Raksha Bandhan">
</div>

<div id="holi" class="festival-card">
    <h2>Holi</h2>
    <p>The festival of Holi celebrates the victory of good over evil, based on the legend of Prahlad and Holika. The demon king Hiranyakashipu commanded his sister, Holika, to sit in a bonfire with his son Prahlad, who worshipped Lord Vishnu. Prahlad's devotion protected him, while the wicked Holika was burned, proving that faith and goodness always triumph.</p>
    <img src="https://img.freepik.com/premium-vector/vector-cartoon-colorful-happy-holi-festival-background-design_620614-194.jpg?w=900" alt="Holi">
</div>

<div id="diwali" class="festival-card">
    <h2>Diwali</h2>
    <p>Diwali (Deepavali) is the Hindu Festival of Lights, symbolizing the victory of light over darkness, good over evil, and knowledge over ignorance. It is a five-day festival, with the most common origin story celebrating the triumphant return of Lord Rama to his kingdom after defeating the demon king Ravana. On the main day, people light thousands of oil lamps (diyas), share sweets and gifts, and celebrate with fireworks.</p>
    <img src="https://img.freepik.com/premium-photo/diwali-cartoon-images_1255560-499.jpg" alt="Diwali">
</div>

